column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

It was a similar size yarding in numbers at Muchea today with just 38 head less than last week. Presented were generous runs of both local and pastoral grown cattle and heavy yearlings showing either finished weights or suited to short feedlot stints along with excellent runs of well-bred weaners and prime cows. Large lines of pastoral stores including cows, steers and heifers along with bulls targeted at Live shipping were also offered.
Weaners sold to similar rates to last week with steers selling from 290c to 362c while weaner heifers returned 200c to 280c/kg. Yearlings enjoyed gains of around 10c as Lighter yearling steers sold from 240c to 310c and with more weight and finish up to 378c/kg. Yearling heifers also gained 10c with the lighter heifers selling from 228c to 278c and in better condition sold to a top of 320c/kg.
Pastoral steer calves ranged from 115c to 280c while lighter pastoral heifer were making from 80c to 180c and with more frame and cover from 208c to 240c/kg.
Grown steers gained 10c selling from 220c to 296c while grown heifers held firm on last weeks gain making 180c to 270c/kg.   Light cows sold from 50c to 162c, medium cows eased another 10c selling to 190c and apart from 1 cow selling to 238c, most heavy cows were back 10c selling from 180c to 212c/kg.
Competition on shipping bulls was solid selling to a top of 308c while slaughter bulls remained firm to return 180c to 212c/kg.
Terry Birkin NLIS.
